Anatomy:
The organisation is typical of 
Amphoriscidae
, with an inarticulate skeleton formed mainly by giant cortical tetractines (
Fig. 10B
). Smaller tetractines also occur in the cortex and are less abundant than the giant ones. Trichoxeas are present (
Fig. 10C
). The inarticulation of the skeleton is due to the apical actine of the cortical tetractines and the unpaired actines of subatrial triactines (
Fig. 10D
). The atrial region is comprised exclusively of tetractines with short apical actines (
Fig. 10E, F
). These short apical actines and those of the giant cortical tetractines perforate the atrial cavity, making the atrial surface hispid.

Subatrial triactines: Actines are cylindrical to slightly conical, with blunt tips. The paired actines are curved from the base to the tips and are always smaller than the unpaired one (
Fig. 11B
).

Distribution: Mediterranean Sea and Plymouth , United Kingdom (BMNH 1955.12.13.9; see remarks of
A. chrysalis
). Corresponding MEOW: Western Mediterranean and Celtic Seas (
Spalding et al . 2007
).
